      "title": "Equation of chord of contact of circle",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Chord of Contact</strong></h3><p><strong>1) If from any point $\\text{T}$ outside a circle two tangents $\\text{TP}$ and $\\text{TQ}$ be drawn to the circle, the straight line $\\text{PQ}$ joining the points of contact is called the chord of contact of tangents from $\\text{T}$. The equation of chord of contact of tangents to the circle at ${{\\text{x}}^{2}}+{{\\text{y}}^{2}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$ is given by&nbsp;</strong></p><p>$\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$</p><p>Proof:&nbsp;</p><p>Let $\\text{T}$ be the point $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ and $\\text{P}$ and $\\text{Q}$ the points $\\left( \\text{x'},\\text{y'} \\right)$ and $\\left( \\text{x''},\\text{y''} \\right)$ respectively.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"267\" height=\"175\">&nbsp;</p><p>The tangent at $\\text{P}$ is ${x}'+{y}'={{a}^{2}}$ … (1)</p><p>and that at $\\text{Q}$ is, $\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}^{\\text{ }\\!\\!'\\!\\!\\text{ }}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}^{\\text{ }\\!\\!'\\!\\!\\text{ }}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$ … (2)</p><p>Since, these tangents pass through $\\text{T}$, its coordinates $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$</p><p>must satisfy both (1) and (2).</p><p>Hence ${{\\text{x}}_{1}}\\text{x''}+{{\\text{y}}_{1}}\\text{y''}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$ … (3)</p><p>and ${{\\text{x}}_{1}}\\text{x''}+{{\\text{y}}_{1}}\\text{y''}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$ … (4)</p><p>The equation to $\\text{PQ}$ is then,</p><p>$\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$ … (5)</p><p>For, since (3) is true, it follows that the point ( $\\left. \\text{x'},\\text{y'} \\right)$, i.e., $\\text{P}$, lies on (5). Also, since (4) is true, it follows that the point ( $\\left. \\text{x''},\\text{y''} \\right)$, i.e., $\\text{Q}$, lies on (5).</p><p>Hence, both $\\text{P}$ and $\\text{Q}$ lie on the straight line (5), i.e., (5), is the equation to the required chord of contact.</p><p>If the point $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ lie within the circle the argument of the preceding article will show that the line joining the (imaginary) points of contact of the two (imaginary) tangents drawn from $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ is $\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}={{\\text{a}}^{2}}$.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>2) The equation of the chord of the circle ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2gx+2fy+c=0$ whose middle point is $\\left( {{x}_{1}},{{y}_{1}} \\right)$ &nbsp;is given by $\\mathbf{T}={{\\mathbf{S}}_{1}}$ where $\\text{T}\\equiv \\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{g}\\left( \\text{x}+{{\\text{x}}_{1}} \\right)+\\text{f}\\left( \\text{y}+{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)+\\text{c}$ and $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{S}}_{1}}\\equiv \\text{x}_{1}^{2}+\\text{y}_{1}^{2}+2\\text{g}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+2\\text{f}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{c}$&nbsp;</strong></p><p>Proof:&nbsp;</p><p>The equation of given circle is ${{x}^{2}}+{{y}^{2}}+2gx+2fy+c=0\\ldots \\left( 1 \\right)$</p><p>Its Centre is $\\text{C}\\equiv \\left( -\\text{g},-\\text{f} \\right)$</p><p>Let $\\text{PQ}$ be the chord whose mid-points is $\\text{L}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"166\" height=\"190\">&nbsp;</p><p>We have to find the equation of the chord $\\text{PQ}$ of the circle</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{l}} {} &amp; \\text{ Slope }~\\text{ of }~\\text{ }CL=\\frac{{{y}_{1}}+f}{{{x}_{1}}+g} \\\\ {} &amp; \\text{ Since }~\\text{ }CL\\bot PQ \\\\ \\therefore \\text{ } &amp; \\text{ slope }~\\text{ of }~\\text{ }PQ=\\frac{{{x}_{1}}+g}{{{y}_{1}}+f} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>Now equation of chord PQ is $y-{{y}_{1}}=\\frac{{{x}_{1}}+g}{{{y}_{1}}+f}\\left( x-{{x}_{1}} \\right)$</p><p>or $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\left( \\text{y}-{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)\\left( {{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{f} \\right)=-\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{g} \\right)\\left( \\text{x}-{{\\text{x}}_{1}} \\right)$</p><p>or $\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}-\\text{y}_{1}^{2}+\\text{yf}-{{\\text{y}}_{1}}\\text{f}=-\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{x}_{1}^{2}-\\text{xg}+\\text{g}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}$</p><p>or $\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{gx}+\\text{fy}=\\text{x}_{1}^{2}+\\text{y}_{1}^{2}+\\text{g}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{f}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}$</p><p>Adding $\\text{g}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{f}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{c}$ to both sides, we get</p><p>$\\text{x}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+\\text{y}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{g}\\left( \\text{x}+{{\\text{x}}_{1}} \\right)+\\text{f}\\left( \\text{y}+{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)+\\text{c}=\\text{x}_{1}^{2}+\\text{y}_{1}^{2}+2\\text{g}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}+2\\text{f}{{\\text{y}}_{1}}+\\text{c}$</p><p>This is the required equation of the chord $\\text{PQ}$ whose mid-point is $\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$.</p><p><strong>Note: </strong>This equation can be written as $\\text{T}={{\\text{S}}_{1}}$,</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd30c03b9dcaf1afe9b1"
    }
